{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Valid JSON payloads containing markdown-heavy strings parse successfully and proceed through normal hook input handling.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between JSON parsing and downstream hook-input handling, not just pure parsing logic. A unit test of `JSON.parse`-equivalent logic would miss wiring bugs where parsed markdown-heavy fields are mishandled by the next module. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: it does not require real process/OS/network (`REAL-INFRA` no), no AI output (`LLM-DEP` no), and no multi-agent chain.","test_description":"Run an in-process test wiring parser + hook input handler + trace collector. Feed valid JSON whose string fields include code fences, backticks, and `$vars`; assert parse succeeds, handler returns normal success path, and no parse-failure trace is emitted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Truly malformed JSON payloads produce a `json_parse_failed` trace record with enough context to diagnose the malformed section.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is parser error propagation into structured trace context, which is a module-boundary interaction (parser -> tracing). Unit-only checks of exception text can miss dropped/incorrect trace fields. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: no requirement for real subprocess or OS I/O, only malformed payload handling and trace content.","test_description":"In-process integration test with parser + trace sink stub. Provide malformed JSON variants (unterminated string, broken escape, truncated object). Assert `json_parse_failed` trace exists and includes diagnostic context (offset/snippet/error) sufficient to localize malformed section.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The local error-policy path maps parse failure to a handled result (no throw) and marks telemetry intent.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior explicitly targets policy mapping plus telemetry intent marking after parse failure; this is cross-module control-flow/state propagation. Unit tests of policy function alone may miss integration regressions where parse errors are not transformed correctly. Higher levels are disqualified: behavior says 'local error-policy path' (no real OS/network/process requirement), and no AI dependency.","test_description":"Wire parser error output into error-policy module and telemetry-intent recorder in-process. Trigger parse failure and assert returned result is handled (non-throwing), error classification is correct, and telemetry intent flag/event is set.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"In real process execution, malformed stdin does not crash the hook process and still emits the expected trace signal before exit.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires real process execution and malformed stdin handling order before exit. Subprocess lifecycle, stdio buffering, and exit semantics are OS/runtime behaviors that mocks can hide (`REAL-INFRA` yes, `MOCK-HIDE` yes). Agentic/Workflow are disqualified because no AI-model dependency or multi-agent sequence is described.","test_description":"Spawn the real hook executable as a subprocess, pipe malformed JSON to stdin, wait for process exit, and assert: non-crash termination behavior, expected exit classification, and `json_parse_failed` trace signal emitted before process termination.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"A real hook invocation path (stdin -> parser -> trace sink) produces the expected trace artifact when malformed input is supplied.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior text says 'real hook invocation path' and includes stdin endpoint, so minimum boundary includes real I/O path and invocation wiring. In-process fakes could miss framing/streaming/runtime differences in actual invocation (`REAL-INFRA` yes). Higher AI levels are disqualified: deterministic parsing/trace behavior, no model output dependency.","test_description":"Execute the hook via its real invocation entrypoint, send malformed stdin payload, and validate the produced trace artifact in the actual sink/output channel (or persisted artifact) matches expected `json_parse_failed` semantics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.86,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Regression tests distinguish malformed-JSON failures from valid-markdown payloads, preventing false attribution to markdown content itself.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is a comparative classification/regression behavior across parser + error attribution/tracing logic. Unit tests of parser alone may not catch misattribution in the reporting path. System was considered but rejected because behavior text does not require real subprocess/OS path, only correct distinction between two input classes. No AI dependency.","test_description":"Parameterized in-process regression test over two cohorts: valid JSON with markdown-heavy strings and truly malformed JSON. Assert first cohort never emits `json_parse_failed`, second always does, and attribution/message clearly points to JSON malformation rather than markdown constructs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":